Crossposted-To: comp.os.ms-windows.advocacy
From: muzok@microsoft.com (Muzaffer Kal)
Subject: Re: NT versus Linux
Date: 15 Sep 93 15:29:57 GMT

In article <strobl.747830944@gmd.de> strobl@gmd.de wrote:
> > Even today 16M of physical memory is enough for most of
> >the systems and apps. 
> 
> Well, this is quite similar to the argument twelve years ago: most

No it's not. Don't forget that I am comparing a "16M system which is 
usefull today" vs a "16MB cpu which was release 10 years ago". 

> 
> >Also there is nothing implicit in the software architecture 
> >of 68000 which creates a 16MB limit. 
> 
> The very same statement can be made about the 80286.
> 

Again, I was comparing 68000 to 8086.

> 
> But perhaps there was something implicit in the design for a software system
> like the Macs OS which requires such an implementation? The fact that 
> Windows took a very similar approach could make one believe so.

MS Windows took the approach it took, because it didn't have a CPU with 32 bit
registers and flat address space. There was no other choice. On the other hand
Apple chose segmented architecture.

> There are FOUR segment registers, and the 8K LDT/GDT limit is just as 
> invisible to ordinary application programs as the aforementioned 24 bit

So if you are an ordinary application programmer, you can allocate 8K 100 bytes
and run out of segment descriptors. (OK, I aggree that you should sub-allocate
but that seems to take more than an ordinary app, these days)

Also, the programmer is extremely well aware of the 4 segment registers and swapping,
comparing and allocating them is a royal pain.

Muzaffer

The views expressed in this message are my own and
in no way reflect the views of Microsoft Corporation.

